EUR Receivable Hedge Framing – Aerospace Manufacturer
Created by: Kiley Gennerman Updated by: Kiley Gennerman Date Created: 2026-07-21 Date Updated: 2026-07-21 
 
Executive Summary 
Our firm is owed €20,000,000 (converted at spot) in one year from a European customer under an aerospace sales contract, and that payment will convert to USD at whatever rate prevails at maturity. Because EURUSD can move meaningfully over a 12-month window, our USD proceeds are exposed to currency risk we do not currently manage. This memo lays out the exposure, why it matters to our bottom line, and three standard ways to hedge it a forward contract, a money market hedge, and options each with different cost and flexibility trade-offs. It closes with the plan for the next four project stages, which will turn this framing into a fully specified, market-data-driven hedge model and a final recommendation.
 
Background & Objectives
We have a $20,000,000 EUR-denominated receivable due in one year. The exposure arises because the contract is priced in euros while our reporting currency is USD, so the amount we ultimately collect depends on the EURUSD rate at settlement. If the euro weakens against the dollar between now and maturity, our realized USD proceeds fall short of the amount budgeted at signing directly compressing margin on the deal. The objective of this workstream is to evaluate hedging strategies that protect the USD value of this receivable while keeping reasonable upside if the euro strengthens instead.
 
Methods
We are evaluating three hedge families:
•	Forward contract: Locks in a fixed EURUSD conversion rate today for the full $20M notional. Pros: no upfront premium, complete rate certainty. Cons: forfeits any benefit if EUR strengthens, and it's a binding obligation.
•	Money market hedge: Borrow EUR now, convert to USD, invest, and repay the loan with the receivable at maturity. Pros: synthetically replicates a forward using cash markets, useful if forward pricing looks unfavorable. Cons: requires access to EUR credit lines and adds balance-sheet complexity.
•	Options (EUR put): Buy a put-on EUR to set a worst-case floor while retaining upside if EUR appreciates. Pros: asymmetric protection. Cons: costs an upfront premium regardless of outcome.
 
